   				<hr color="#cc0000">
 				<p style="font-size:80%;">Price in US Dollars</p>
				<p>The Cook Islands Foundation Act 2012 is a modern and innovative piece of legislation drawing from the experiences and features of foundation law in other financial centres, and adding Cook Islands specialist asset provisions.
				<p>&nbsp;</p>
				<p>A foundation is a registered legal entity which is formed by a person known as the founder who provides assets to be administered by the foundation. Unlike a Trust, a foundation is a separate legal entity and is managed by a council, governed by its rules and may have either beneficiaries or be established for charitable purposes. Contrary to trust beneficiaries who have equitable rights, the foundation beneficiaries have contractual rights in relation to the assets of the foundation.</p>
				<p>&nbsp;</p>
				<p>The cost to establish and annually renew a foundation is higher than setting up a company but is much lower than setting up a Trust, making it an attractive option for many.</p>
				<p>&nbsp;</p>
				<h2>Common uses of foundations are:</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Asset and investment holding</li></li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Asset accumulation and protection</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Avoidance of forced heirship rules</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Art collections</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Consolidation of worldwide assets in a centralized location</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Charitable purposes</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>International income, capital gains, estate tax, inheritance tax planning</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Pension funds</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Separation of voting and economic benefits</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Succession planning</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Special financing arrangements</li>
				</ul>
				<p>&nbsp;</p>
				<ul>
					<li>Benefits of a Cook Islands Foundation:</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Privacy and confidentiality in terms of access to information</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>While the instrument of a foundation is required to be filed at the Government Registry, there is no requirements to file a foundation’s rules. It is also not obligatory to state in the instrument, the names of the founder, enforcer or the beneficiaries. It is also not mandatory to file the name of the council members with the Registry.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Nil Cook Islands taxation on income, exempt from withholding tax and stamp duty.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Low minimum initial assets – a value of not less than Ten United States Dollars (US$10) or equivalent in any currency.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Strong asset protection as foundation assets are the property of only the foundation. Neither the founder nor beneficiaries have any interest in foundation assets. Beneficiaries’ rights to information may be restricted. It has a 2 year statute of limitations for creditors’ claims coupled with high onus of proof.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Succession and tax planning as management and control will be vested in the foundation council (which may be located offshore). Foundation assets can be passed on from one generation to the next and do not become beneficiary’s assets unless distributed in accordance to the provisions of the foundation’s Rules or regulations.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Ease of administration due there are no annual audit requirement, nor to file financial accounts or annual return in the Cook Islands. No annual meeting requirement for Council Members, the founders or enforcer. </li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Founder’s reserve powers allows the right to appoint or remove Council Members, Enforcers, add or exclude beneficiaries.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Enforcer as an option to give limited veto power for certain foundation decision,</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Foreign language (non-English) documents is permissible, accompanied by a translation in English.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Provides for the redomicilation and migration in and out of Cook Islands.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>Duration – may be limited or unlimited. No rule against perpetuities.</li>
				</ul>
				<ul>
					<li>The Act provides for the termination, dissolution and revocation of a foundation, either in whole or part.</li>
				</ul>
				<h1>Key Features</hi>
